caption: Located along the banks of the Seine, is the quirky, secondhand book sellers, definitely worth a visit during a walk, it is very interesting the stuff they have on offer not just books.
Nice posters and vintage stuff

Nice walk full of stalls. Although there are especially second-hand books, you can also buy The Little Prince in French at a very good price.
Along the Seine. You can find everything there: postcards, pins, old books, posters. A must-have in Parisian life

The second-hand booksellers on the banks of the Seine in Paris are part of the folkloric institutions of the City of Lights. Old magazines, vintage postcards, collectible books, you can find a little bit of everything, lots of second-hand goods and above all great stories when you listen to the owners of the boxes with their well-filled stalls. This is perhaps the most beautiful thing you can find there. Paper memories and poetry.
A must in Paris. Full of charm. We recommend it, it’s a mythical and magical place.

Bookstores are an integral part of the history of Paris. Born during the 16th century, it was under Napoleon I that they could spread out along the Seine, according to specific rules. They can be found installed over 3 km of both banks: from Pont Marie to Pont des Arts and from Pont Sully to Pont Royal.
Definitely a must when visiting Paris! There are so many interesting things to find here and buy for little money.

If you are going to look for new books, it is not your place. You find old books in good condition and fair prices. But the important thing is that they are on the banks of the Seine and that gives them a particular charm. Generally the clerks are friendly even if you don't speak French.

The second-hand booksellers say that I supported them when they were almost displaced for the Olympics. A week ago I bought magnets in Paris for foreign friends, I was received like a dog by two second-hand booksellers, in no longer with exorbitant prices I said to myself it's hopeless and if foreigners are received like that for The “poor France” Olympics
Take a walk and buy quality (second-hand) books during the walk. We can only do this in Paris. I found my happiness in philosophy.
Don't move the bookstores and secure the platforms with barriers and security guards for a few hours of parade for the 2024 Olympic Games, it's common sense, you have to be pragmatic.
Bookstores are part of the heritage of Paris.  I find it shameful that they are being asked to leave due to Olympic security concerns.
